{"key":"processedPost-12770889","value":{"id":12770889,"first":12770491,"last":12848251,"when":1277002081,"utime":"06/20/10 05:48 AM","content":"That's a method that will fail with straw more than it succeeds.&nbsp; You can use a stove to heat the water, but pour it into a container and let it cool down to about 170F before adding the straw.&nbsp; If you sterilize the straw, it's more likely to contaminate.&nbsp; You want to preserve the beneficial bacteria, so don't subject it to boiling temp water.&nbsp; Follow the video posted above.<br /><br />The dish soap is a wetting agent.&nbsp; It helps the straw to hydrate in two hours rather than soaking it 24 hours before pasteurizing.&nbsp; It also helps to kill some of the bacteria and most of the mold spores.&nbsp; Some growers in third world countries use soap-only pasteurization, but they also have a high contamination rate.&nbsp; However, if they don't have access to electricity, gas, or wood to heat the water, it's one method to get by with.<br />RR","title":"Re: Straw Pasturaization"}}